<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06104043 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06104043 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  ARIZONA; CIVIL; LEADER; HOLIDAY; CONTROVERSY; DECREASE; MONEY  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  The Phoenix andamp; Valley of the Sun Convention andamp; Visitors Bureau has put a $142million price tag on the state's rejection of a paid holiday honoring the Rev.Martin Luther King Jr.;    The bureau says the Phoenix area will be out $132million in lost revenues and $10.1 million in lost taxes because of groups'canceling conventions from 1987 to 1996.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  PHOENIX LOST $142 MILLION IN KING FLAP  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     Organizations have been boycotting Arizona for four years as a result ofthe state's failure to adopt a holiday for the slain civil-rights leader. Theboycotts accelerated after Nov. 6, when voters defeated propositions thatwould have established a King holiday.;    The figures released Thursday werecompiled by Arizona State University.;    David Radcliffe, president of thevisitors bureau, said he hopes the information will influence voters toapprove the holiday next year.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Arizona Republic  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Phoenix  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910413  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Saturday  </DAY><MONTH>  April  </MONTH><PG.COL>  20A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  135  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Saturday April 13, 199100104043,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>